      official docs (antigravity.google/docs/rules-workflows). Pre-fix our
      install was effectively a no-op for end users since the IDE never read
      `.agents/workflows/`. Renamed the source dir, switched _TOOL_FILES["agents"]
      from a single tuple to a list-of-tuples so `codedna install --tools agents`
      now writes BOTH AGENTS.md (cross-vendor, always-on rules — works on
      Antigravity v1.20.3+, OpenCode, Cursor, Claude Code) AND
      .agent/workflows/codedna.md (workflow triggered with /codedna). Auto-detect
      now recognises Antigravity via .agent/, GEMINI.md, .gemini/. install.sh
      do_agents() rewritten with skip-if-exists for AGENTS.md so it doesn't
      clobber an OpenCode setup. Pytest 185 passed/0 failed; CLI E2E and
      install.sh E2E both verified via local file:// shims. Issue #9 (wiki
      bootstrap OOM on GGUF/dataset files) is tracked separately, not in this
      commit.

  - agent: claude-opus-4-7
    provider: anthropic
    date: 2026-04-30
    session_id: s_20260430_wiki_oom
    task: "fix #9: codedna wiki bootstrap OOM on large non-source files"
    changed:
      - codedna_tool/wiki.py
      - tests/test_wiki.py
      - CHANGELOG.md
    visited:
      - codedna_tool/wiki.py
      - codedna_tool/cli.py
      - codedna_tool/languages/__init__.py
      - tests/test_wiki.py
    message: >
      Pre-fix _extract_fields did path.read_text() which loaded each file fully
      into RAM before checking for a CodeDNA header. On repos containing GGUF
      model weights or multi-GB datasets, this raised MemoryError (reported by
      @DATEx2 in issue #9; traceback showed the crash at wiki.py:87 inside
      pathlib's read_text → f.read → MemoryError on 5+ GB files). Fix reads
      only the first 16 KB (HEADER_READ_BYTES) — the L1 header always fits
      well within that. Adds a cheap "exports:" pre-check to skip files
      without an annotation before any further work, and a regex fallback for
      Python files where the 16 KB cut breaks ast.parse() syntax (extracts
      the leading triple-quoted docstring directly). Wiki output is byte-for-byte
      unchanged on annotated files (verified by the existing test suite passing
      unmodified). Two regression tests added: 5 MB binary in repo doesn't
      crash; Python file with 60 KB body after docstring still gets its header.
      Smoke test on a 50 MB random binary: peak memory 177 MB, vault correct.
      L2 (function Rules:) is not extracted by wiki bootstrap — confirmed by
      reading _page_markdown which renders only L1 fields.

  - agent: claude-opus-4-7
    provider: anthropic
    date: 2026-04-30
    session_id: s_20260430_init_dataloss
    task: "fix #10: codedna init silently destroyed multi-line module docstrings"
    changed:
      - codedna_tool/cli.py
      - tests/test_cli.py
      - CHANGELOG.md
    visited:
      - codedna_tool/cli.py
      - tests/test_cli.py
      - CHANGELOG.md
    message: >
      Test-first: 4 failing tests (TestBuildDocstring + TestInit) reproducing
      reporter's exact case (yuzi-co), then fix. Pre-fix build_module_docstring
      called _purpose(info.docstring) which extracted only the first line; the
      rest of the docstring was discarded. inject_module_docstring then replaced
      the entire existing string-statement with the new (truncated) docstring,
      so prose / examples / notes / ASCII diagrams below the summary line were
      lost silently. Reporter said this erased migration docs and architectural
      notes across ~745 Python files in their repo. Fix: new internal helper
      _extract_docstring_body() returns the body verbatim (everything after the
      first line), stripping any CodeDNA field lines (exports/used_by/related/
      wiki/rules/agent/message) and their indented continuations so init
      --force over an annotated file doesn't emit duplicate fields. Body is
      spliced between the summary line and the CodeDNA fields. Smoke-tested on
      reporter's repro: file goes from 17 → 23 lines (was 17 → 6 pre-fix), all
      6 critical body lines preserved verbatim. 191 passed / 0 failed.
      Note: had to add `import re` at module top — _CODEDNA_FIELD_RE regex
      needed it. First test run after fix initially failed because of that
      missing import; spotted via NameError in the traceback and corrected.
